<h2 id="deliverability">The Deliverability Problem Nobody Talks About</h2>

<p>The most important factor in cold email success is not the tool you use — it is your sending infrastructure. A poorly configured sending domain will land in spam regardless of which tool you use. Here is what actually matters:</p>

<p><strong>Domain age and warmup:</strong> A fresh domain (registered less than 30 days ago) will almost always land in spam for the first 2–4 weeks of sending, regardless of warmup tool. The standard recommendation is to register sending domains 60+ days before your first campaign and run a warmup tool for at least 30 days before sending cold outreach.</p>

<p><strong>DNS configuration:</strong> SPF, DKIM, and DMARC records must be correctly configured on every sending domain. All major cold email tools provide setup guides, but this is the most common source of deliverability problems for new users. Google's <a href="https://postmaster.google.com" target="_blank" rel="noopener">Postmaster Tools</a> and <a href="https://mxtoolbox.com" target="_blank" rel="noopener">MXToolbox</a> are free tools for diagnosing DNS issues.</p>

<p><strong>Sending volume and ramp:</strong> Starting a new domain at 100 emails per day on day one is a reliable way to get blacklisted. The standard ramp is: 20 emails/day in week 1, 40 in week 2, 80 in week 3, 150 in week 4, then scale from there. All major cold email tools support sending limits per account to enforce this.</p>

<p><strong>List quality:</strong> A 5%+ bounce rate will trigger spam filters at Gmail and Outlook. Verify your contact list with a tool like NeverBounce or ZeroBounce before importing it into your cold email platform. Most cold email tools include basic bounce handling, but they cannot fix a list with 20% invalid addresses.</p>

<p><strong>The inbox rotation strategy:</strong> The most effective deliverability strategy in 2026 is to spread sends across multiple email accounts on multiple domains. Instead of sending 500 emails/day from one account, send 50 emails/day from 10 accounts across 3–5 domains. Instantly and Smartlead both support this natively. This approach distributes the sending reputation risk and allows you to scale volume without triggering spam filters.</p>

